\pard\plain\s30\ql\sb120\sa120\keep\widctlpar\f0\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 {Figure {\*\bkmkstart BMfig_intxncues}1{\*\bkmkend BMfig_intxncues}: {\i0\scaps0\b Nonlinear phenological responses to warming can occur when multiple cues shift in concert with climate change.} Much research focuses on how warming increases forcing, but warming may also alter other cues, including photoperiod experienced near the time of the event (yellow line), which is expected to shorten, and chilling (blue lines), which may either increase or decrease (a). Shifts in forcing alongside shifts in a second cue may produce non-linearities due to the interaction between cues (b-c) showing the effect of: forcing-only (dashed line), both cues without an interaction (\lquote noint\rquote ), and both cues with an interaction (labeled as \lquote weak\rquote  and \lquote strong\rquote ). The overall change in budburst day predicted with warming depends on the sign of the second cue (negative in b, positive in c), as well as its strength (weak/strong).}{\field{\*\fldinst TC "1 {\i0\scaps0\b Nonlinear phenological responses to warming can occur when multiple cues shift in concert with climate change.} Much research focuses on how warming increases forcing, but warming may also alter other cues, including photoperiod experienced near the time of the event (yellow line), which is expected to shorten, and chilling (blue lines), which may either increase or decrease (a). Shifts in forcing alongside shifts in a second cue may produce non-linearities due to the interaction between cues (b-c) showing the effect of: forcing-only (dashed line), both cues without an interaction (\lquote noint\rquote ), and both cues with an interaction (labeled as \lquote weak\rquote  and \lquote strong\rquote ). The overall change in budburst day predicted with warming depends on the sign of the second cue (negative in b, positive in c), as well as its strength (weak/strong)." \\f f}{\fldrslt }}\par
